Check constraints on plain delta — quality without a pipeline.

Not every table needs a full pipeline framework. Plain delta tables support check constraints — predicates that are enforced on every write. You add one with an alter-table statement, for example requiring that amount is positive, or that currency is one of an allowed set.

There are three things that distinguish them from expectations. Check constraints fail the write on violation — there's no drop-and-log option. They're table-level, not pipeline-level, so they apply to every write, no matter who's writing. And they're cheaper to set up — just one alter-table — but they're less expressive.

So here's how the exam contrasts the two. If the question says reject bad rows at write time on a plain delta table, the answer is check constraints. If the question says track violations, or drop bad rows, or fail the pipeline based on severity, the answer is expectations.
